TY  - JOUR
T1  - Composing The Reflected Best-Self Portrait: Building Pathways For Becoming Extraordinary In Work Organizations
AU  - Roberts, Laura Morgan
AU  - Dutton, Jane E.
AU  - Spreitzer, Gretchen M.
AU  - Heaphy, Emily D.
AU  - Quinn, Robert E.
Y1  - 2005/10/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.18378874
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.18378874
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 712
EP  - 736
VL  - 30
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We present a theory of how individuals compose their reflected best-self portrait, which we define as a changing self-knowledge structure about who one is at one's best. We posit that people compose their reflected best-self portrait through social experiences that draw on intrapsychic and interpersonal resources. By weaving together microlevel theories of personal change and macrolevel theories of human resource development, our theory reveals an important means by which work organizations affect people's capacity to realize their potential.
AB  - We present a theory of how individuals compose their reflected best-self portrait, which we define as a changing self-knowledge structure about who one is at one's best. We posit that people compose their reflected best-self portrait through social experiences that draw on intrapsychic and interpersonal resources. By weaving together microlevel theories of personal change and macrolevel theories of human resource development, our theory reveals an important means by which work organizations affect people's capacity to realize their potential.
