TY  - JOUR
T1  - Just Joking Around? Employee Humor Expression As An Ingratiatory Behavior
AU  - Cooper, Cecily D.
Y1  - 2005/10/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.18378877
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.18378877
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 765
EP  - 776
VL  - 30
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Previous research on ingratiation in organizations has identified various categories of ingratiatory behaviors. However, these studies have failed to mention or investigate the ingratiatory power of humor. I integrate past research on ingratiation with research on humor in organizations to propose humor as a type of ingratiatory behavior in the workplace. I describe how humor affects targets, including determinants of humor's effectiveness as an ingratiation strategy, and various outcomes of humor as an ingratiation tactic.
AB  - Previous research on ingratiation in organizations has identified various categories of ingratiatory behaviors. However, these studies have failed to mention or investigate the ingratiatory power of humor. I integrate past research on ingratiation with research on humor in organizations to propose humor as a type of ingratiatory behavior in the workplace. I describe how humor affects targets, including determinants of humor's effectiveness as an ingratiation strategy, and various outcomes of humor as an ingratiation tactic.
